# A example STELF file
We start in literate mode, where we can write markdown (like this!). The only charecter we can't write is the percent sign, but we can if we escape it as %%%.
## The Basic Syntax
%sort τ %. Sort of all types. After the `%%%.` sign, we are back in the "outer" literate mode
%sort e %. 
Expressions, not that much special here, also, we can use as many newlines as we wish in outer mode (or any other chareters, like this `‾\(ツ)/‾` )
### Abbreviations
%inline type τ %. Of course, writing out τ on a normal keyboard is a bit of a pain (that's why TeX has macros like $\tau$), so we can define an abbreviation for it.
> [!TIP] In STELF, the only reserved symbols (symbols that not allowed in identifiers) is the percent sign, as well as `()[]{}`, so we are free to use `type` as an identifier
%inline sort type %. Even commands without the prefix can be used as identifiers, so this is perfectly valid. 
%inline expr e %. We can also define namespaces (a.k.a, scopes) to group definitions together and avoid name clashes
## Syntax of Types
%scope τ %{ 
  %. > [!NOTE] `->` is a perfectly valid identifier
  %term -> 
    %pi type % This is the new chain syntax
    %-> type % We use the prefixed symbol as an arrow
    %-> type % Also, this is an inline comment.
    %.
  %. The above could also be written 
  %[ `%term -> {_ type} {_ type} type` %]
%}

...


